    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEMS DIAGNOSTICS - Circuit Diagnostics -
        Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS)</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3356" filename="../figd33/D3356.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="472px"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for the Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS)</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Function Diagram for the VSS includes the following:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>World Transmission Electronic Control (WTEC) ECM</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Cruise Control, Power Takeoff, Road Speed Limit</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>Function</title>
            </para>
            <para>The Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS) is a magnetic pick-up sensor located in the transmission. The VSS reads
                the rotation of a 16 toothed gear and produces a sine wave signal. The ECM processes the sine wave
                signal to calculate vehicle speed. The Drivetrain Datalink (CAN 1) transmits the calculated speed to the
                speedometer. The calculated speed also assists in control strategies that include Cruise Control, Power
                Takeoff, and Road Speed Limiting.
            </para>
            <para>Allison WTEC MD and 2000 series transmissions use an internal VSS that sends a signal to the
                transmission module. The transmission module processes the signal and sends a square wave signal to the
                engine ECM.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>VSS Circuit Operation</title>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3357" filename="../figd33/D3357.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"/>
                <caption>VSS Circuit Diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>
                <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            </para>
            <para>The ECM performs diagnostic checks on the VSS circuit when the engine is operating at 0 mph. The ECM
                transmits a voltage signal on the VSS circuit and determines if the return voltage is out of range high
                or low. When a fault condition is detected, the ECM disables the cruise control and power takeoff. If
                the road speed limiting option is enabled, the ECM will limit engine rpm for all gears.
            </para>
            <para>The ECM will not set DTCs for VSS circuit failure for vehicles equipped with Allison MD (WTEC) and
                2000 series transmissions. Vehicles equipped with MD transmissions only diagnose the communication
                circuit (CAN 1) between the engine and transmission module.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>See truck Chassis Electrical Circuit Diagram manual for circuit numbers, connector and fuse
                        locations. To diagnose MD VSS sensor problems, see truck Electrical System Troubleshooting Guide
                        and Allison WTEC maintenance and diagnostic manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>VSS Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs)</title>
            </para>
            <para>DTCs are read using the Electronic Service Tool (EST) or by counting the flashes from the amber and
                red ENGINE lamp.
            </para>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc141">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 141</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">Out of Range Low</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 141 is set by the ECM when an out of range low condition is detected in the VSS circuit.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>When DTC 141 is active the amber ENGINE lamp is not illuminated.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc142">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 142</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">Out of Range High</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 142 is set by the ECM when an out of range high condition is detected in the VSS
                        circuit.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>When DTC 142 is active the amber ENGINE lamp is not illuminated.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The ECM monitors voltage on V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        A and will adjust signal values for the sensors that use V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        A for operation. If a sensor or circuit pulls V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        lower than 5V, the ECM may set out of range high DTCs for the sensors that operate on V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        B (APS, BAP, B+, and VSS).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc215">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 215</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">Signal Frequency Out of Range High</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 215 is set by the ECM when the ECM detects a VSS signal greater than 4365 Hz.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>Tools</title>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Service Tool (EST) with INTUNE and Master Diagnostics software</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>International&#174; EZ-Tech Interface Cable</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>International&#174; J1939 Interface Cable</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Electrical System Troubleshooting Guide (truck manual)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Electrical Circuit Diagrams (truck manual)</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>VSS Pin Point Diagnostics</title>
            <para>The VSS circuit requires the use of vehicle circuit diagrams. See truck Chassis Electrical Circuit
                Diagram manual for circuit numbers, connector and fuse locations.
            </para>
            <table id="te24007084" tblwidth="pg-wide" frame="bottom">
                <tgroup cols="3">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="2.00in"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.86in"/>
                    <colspec colname="col3" colwidth="3.00*"/>
                    <spanspec namest="col1" nameend="col3" spanname="SPAN1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <warning>
                                    <para>To avoid serious personal injury, possible death, or damage to the engine or
                                        vehicle, always disconnect main negative battery cable first. Always connect the
                                        main negative battery cable last.
                                    </para>
                                </warning>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Connector Voltage Checks</emph>
                                    (Disconnect sensor from harness and turn ignition key ON.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>Test Point</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>Spec</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Comments</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>B to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>2-3V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3" morerows="1">
                                <para>ECM pull up voltage when sensor disconnected. If no voltage present, check for
                                    open or short to ground.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>A to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>2-3V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>-</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Sensor Continuity Checks</emph>
                                    (Check with sensor disconnected and ignition key OFF.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>Test Point</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>Spec</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Comments</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>B to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>>1k&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If &#60;1k&#x2126;, check for short to ground</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>A to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>>1k&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If &#60;1k&#x2126;, check for short to ground</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>B to A</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>600-800&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Manual transmission (measure resistance through sensor)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>B to A</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>Ref Allison Manual</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>MD Automatic Transmission (electronically controlled)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Harness Resistance Checks</emph>
                                    (Turn ignition key OFF. Disconnect negative battery cable and sensor. Install
                                    breakout box on chassis harness only.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-9 to B</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for open circuit.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-10 to A</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for open circuit.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-9 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>>1k&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If &#60;1k&#x2126;, check for short to ground.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-10 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>>1k&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If &#60;1k&#x2126;, check for short to ground.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-10 to X4-9</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>>2V AC</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If &#60;2V AC, check sensor adjustment or replace defective sensor.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">VSS Diagnostic Trouble Code</emph>
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>DTC 141 = ECM detected low voltage across VSS circuit for >0.5 seconds</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>DTC 142 = ECM detected high voltage across VSS circuit for >0.5 seconds</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>DTC 215 = ECM detected VSS frequency signal >4.365 kHz</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If circuit checks are within spec and condition remains, see transmission manual for sensor
                        inspection and adjustment.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
